Integration tests for `ctx_scan::cli::stop_hook`, the Claude Code Stop-hook entry point, asserting it is strictly report-only and never triggers regeneration itself (that's `ctx-run`'s job, invoked separately post-session).

Three behaviors are locked in: (1) on a stale tree, `stop_hook` writes JSON containing `"systemMessage"`, the word `"stale"`, and a `--update` suggestion to its output writer, but the tree must remain stale afterward — verified via `check_run(&base).is_fresh()` staying false, proving the hook doesn't call `update_run` internally; (2) on a tree already made fresh via `update_run`, `stop_hook` must produce empty output — total silence, not just absence of a stale message; (3) when the backlog exceeds `ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS` (files count is `MAX_TARGETS + 1` via `0..=MAX_TARGETS`), the suggested command escalates to `--update --approve` instead of plain `--update`.

`StubAgent` is a trivial `Agent` impl used only to seed a fresh tree via `update_run(&base, &prompts_path(), &agent, false)` — it always returns `"SUMMARY"` and tracks call count (unused by assertions here). `prompts_path()` resolves the workspace's `../../prompts` dir relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`, independent of test cwd — required because `update_run` needs real prompt files to run its summarization flow. Each test uses a uniquely named tmpdir under `std::env::temp_dir()` and cleans up both before (via `fixture`'s `remove_dir_all`) and after itself; tests are not isolated from leftover state if a prior run crashed mid-test, since cleanup happens at start via `fixture`/manual `remove_dir_all` too. `stop_hook`'s signature takes a `&mut Vec<u8>`-like writer (via `&mut out`) for output, and returns a `Result` — errors here aren't currently tested.